"Lyon B.","The strength of El Niño and the spatial extent of tropical drought",2004,"Geophysical Research Letters","31","21",,"L21204 1","4",,,10.1029/2004GL020901,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-13244283009&partnerID=40&md5=27134adbc21a97888031b6cdf54dea99","Intl. Res. Inst. Climate Prediction, Lamont-Doherty Earth Observatory, Columbia University, New York, NY 10964, United States","Lyon, B., Intl. Res. Inst. Climate Prediction, Lamont-Doherty Earth Observatory, Columbia University, New York, NY 10964, United States","During El Niño events, several spatially coherent, nearly synchronous droughts typically develop in teleconnected tropical land areas. These droughts, reflected in below-average tropical mean land area precipitation, are frequently accompanied by multiple and wide ranging impacts. Here it is shown, based on precipitation observations for the past half-century, that there is a remarkably robust relationship between El Niño strength and the spatial extent of drought in the global tropics. Not reported previously, drought covers more than twice the land area in strong versus weak El Niños and in many areas severe drought is shown to be more likely during El Niño than for all other times. The results provide insight into largescale tropical rainfall variability and have implications for future droughts under global warming scenarios. Copyright 2004 by the American Geophysical Union.","1812 Hydrology: Drought; 1854 Hydrology: Precipitation (3354); 3354 Meteorology and Atmospheric Dynamics: Precipitation (1854); 4522 Oceanography: Physical: El Nino","Climate change; Land use; Large scale systems; Precipitation (meteorology); Rain; Tropical engineering; Rainfall variability; Tropical drought; Tropical land areas; Tropical rainfall; Drought; air-sea interaction; drought; El Nino; precipitation (climatology); teleconnection; tropical region",,,,,,"Chiang, J.C.H., Sobel, A., Tropical tropospheric temperature variations caused by ENSO and th